Materials and Methods
Reagents
All chemicals are purchased from Sigma-Aldrich (St. Louis, MO) unless otherwise noted. All reactive PDMS polymers are purchased from Gelest® Inc. (Philadelphia, PA) and used as received. Backbone: vinylmethylsiloxane–dimethylsiloxane copolymer, trimethylsiloxy terminated, ~300 vinyl groups per molecule, MW~50,000 g/mol (VDT-5035). Side chain: mono-hydride terminated polydimethylsiloxane, MW~4,750 g/mol (MCR-H21). Crosslinking chain: hydride-terminated polydimethysiloxane, MW~17,200 g/mol (DMSH25). Extension chain: α-monovinyl-Ω-monohydride terminated polydimethylsiloxane, MW~10,000 g/mol (DMS-HV22).
Bulk rheology
The PDMS linear polymers are mixed at a predetermined mass ratio to achieve different density of crosslinking chains. Catalyst, 2% platinum in xylene, so called Karstedt’s catalyst, is added at the concentration of 5 μl/g, The mixture is cured at 80°C for 40 hours to reach a steady shear storage modulus. Rheological experiments are carried out on a stress controlled rheometer (MCR501, Anton Paar) with 50 mm plate-plate geometry at a gap of 750 μm. Frequency sweeps are performed from 102 to 10−2 Hz at 0.5% stain at temperatures 80°C, 20°C, and −20°C. Changes in normal force due to a gap contraction with temperature are alleviated by adjusting the gap height.
Gel fraction
To quantify the gel fraction of soft elastomers, we use standard Soxhlet method to remove unreacted molecules in the polymerized PDMS-catalyst mixture. We perform the extraction in acetone/n-hexane (50:50) for 60 hours, and then dry the swollen PDMS gel in a vacuum oven at 80°C for 24 hours; after that the mass of PDMS does not decrease. The mass of the insoluble gel fraction is divided by the total mass before extraction and the values are listed in Table 1. The actual value of gel fraction may be larger than the measured value due to possible breakage of bonds upon swelling; swelling soft PDMS elastomers by a large extent leads to a large tension along network strands that may cause bond scission.
Cell growth
To prepare substrates for mammalian cell growth, we place 150μl of the PDMS-catalyst mixture in each well of a 24-well plate and polymerize at the same condition above. We then add 1ml of 1M KOH to each well for 1hr to gently treat the surface of soft PDMS elastomer instead of using plasma oxidation, which can crosslink the surface of PDMS, yielding a stiffer substrate[32]. The surface is silanized by adding 500μl of 1% (v/v) glycidyl propyl trimethoxysilane (Gelest® Inc.) in ethanol, and 500μl 1% (v/v) ammonium solution in water sequentially to each well. After 10 minutes, the surface is cleaned using ethanol, and then 1× phosphate buffered saline (PBS), twice. We add 500 μl of 0.1 mg/ml type 1 collagen to each well and store the plate at 4°C to prevent collagen polymerization but allow the collagen to react to the glycidyl group on the silanized PDMS surface. We repeat the above procedure with fluorescently labeled type 1 collagen[33] and find that the surface coverage of collagen
