Adhesion measurement
To quantify the adhesiveness of soft PDMS elastomers, we use a customized adhesion apparatus consisting of an analytical balance (Mettler ToledoTM AT261) and a linear translation stage (NewportTM LTA-HL) remotely controlled by a motion control software (NewportTM Controller ESP300). The balance records mass with the rate of 1/sec, and the translation stage drives a smooth stainless steel ball with diameter of 3.55 mm moving at a resolution of 0.0074μm. To perform an adhesion test, we lower the ball to a position about 100μm above the surface of a soft PDMS elastomer sample that is placed on the balance; the sample is molded in a Petri dish with diameter of 35mm (NuncTM Petri Dishes) and has a thickness of ~5mm. After that, the ball is driven at a certain rate by the linear translation stage towards the surface of soft PDMS, and indents the sample with a distance ~100 μm. The ball is held at its maximum indentation, waiting 20 minutes for the relaxation of stress due to the compression of soft PDMS sample, and then retracted at the same rate. During the course of indentation and retraction, the force and displacement outputs are collected by customized MATLAB data acquisition software. The adhesion measurement at a certain rate is repeated at least 5 times; between each measurement, the steel ball is cleaned with hexane to remove possible residuals adhered to the ball surface.
